Text: These last four weeks went fast, didn't they?
Ultimately, my main contribution laid in the development of the GUI.
All in all, although I have managed to contribute by implementing some things, I am left feeling somewhat accomplished and somewhat unsatisfied.
First, I am extremely thankful for the online tools and resources which helped me develop the product.
Despite the challenges in the beginning, I somewhat managed to do the minimum research and had learn to implement the minimum viable product.
However, I feel insufficient in my contribution to the research of the algorithms.
I always say "even though you may have not contributed to the project directly, as long as you learn - that is good enough".
Call me a hypocrite, because I feel as though I have not properly learned anything about algorithms that contribute to segmentation.
I did my best to do my own research and understand the theory behind working with images and basic image processing before delving into the algorithms.
However,Â  I would have liked the team to display an open dialogue in knowledge sharing.
Throughout the project, out of curiosity and to cushion my own understanding, I would question the what/when/where/why/how of their work.

I think although some team members were fine with this, I assume some of them may have felt that I was perhaps 'testing their knowledge', because at times subtle defensiveness displayed or unproductive discussion.
Perhaps in the future, I could go about this by suggesting we do some knowledge sharing sessions at one of our meetings.
We did initially mention that this was something we could do - but implementation of that was unsuccessful.
Knowledge sharing sessions would be the best way to develop my own learning and allow the team to be on the same page.

Then again, really driving my own knowledge would be of great benefit as well, rather than putting too much into trying to understand if a team member and I are on the same page, which may result in me annoying them 😅About two weeks ago, I mentioned how the team came up with things we needed to work on.
One of them was to establish proper timeframes for task to prevent working on something for too long.
Ultimately, the team came up with a strategy to play 'planning poker' so that things like this would be prevented.
However, due to unestablished rules, once a deadline had reached, what ultimately happened was that another team member would subconsciously uptake the task without discussion.
I observed that the team member may have been feeling unhappy or insufficient in their contribution to the work due to this.
In the future, it would be best to establish the aftermath of an incomplete milestone.
In this case - ask everyone if someone else taking the task will be the best course of action so that no one feels left out.
I think the most meaningful thing I have learned from this projects is that although we had good team dynamic, there were plenty of things we could have improved on.
As you know, we did team reflections on Friday about what went well and the things we needed to improve on.
I think this is definitely a good idea for a team with good dynamics - however, since I was leading the discussion for the first two weeks, it got pretty taxing.
I think it was because I was putting quite a bit of energy to promoting discussion.

Do not get me wrong, everyone did willingly participate and share, but unbeknownst to me - I felt that these discussions did not anymore improve our dynamic or better organise my own thoughts about the project.
Ultimately, I am appreciative that we have been given the chance to take this course.
I have had the opportunity to work in teams of varying dynamics and discovering how I personally react to different situations.
It gave me opportunity to learn more about myself and assess my reaction and assess what I would like to change about these reactions.
Still a long way ahead for self improvement, but I have enjoyed it so far despite the hiccups.
Overall
